For the past 10 years, Saeeda baji has lived in Borewala, Pakistan, a city famous for its shrines. Her husband, S. H., has operated a timber-selling business for three years while Saeeda baji operates a sewing business, sewing clothes on order from her neighbors, allowing her to share financial burdens with her husband. She is applying for a loan to expand S.’s timber-selling business. <p>

She is the group leader of four other women from her locality:

Safia baji wants a loan to buy thread to resell;
Khursheed baji wants a loan to buy wood to sell;
Sajida baji wants a loan to buy fertilizer to sell;
Yasmeen baji wants a loan to buy a donkey cart for loading. 

This funds for this group loan will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans. If one member does not repay, the other members are responsible.
